  "Idea": "We propose a novel diffusion-based framework for low-light image restoration named 'DynaFusion-Diffuse', which introduces Dynamic Frequency Routing and Progressive Cross-Domain Consistency to achieve adaptive, high-fidelity restoration through intelligent spatial-frequency synergy. Unlike prior methods that apply uniform frequency integration across all regions and timesteps, our approach leverages a Mixture-of-Experts (MoE)-inspired architecture where frequency sub-bands (low, mid, high) are processed by specialized experts conditioned on local content (e.g., edges, textures, flat regions) and global noise level. At each U-Net layer, a routing network predicts activation weights for each expert, enabling sparse, context-aware processing—preserving computational efficiency while enhancing relevant features. To deeply integrate this with spatial processing, we replace rigid skip connections with Dynamic Frequency Routing Gates (DFRGs), which modulate spatial feature maps using activated frequency experts via channel-wise affine transformations. Crucially, these gates are timestep-aware, allowing early diffusion steps to prioritize low-frequency illumination correction and later steps to refine high-frequency details. To address inter-domain misalignment without relying on strict spatial correspondence, we introduce Progressive Cross-Domain Consistency (PCC): instead of aligning spatial and frequency patches at a single step, PCC computes temporal consistency losses across adjacent denoising steps, ensuring that structural evolution in one domain mirrors the other. This is implemented via a momentum-updated teacher-student setup where the student’s multi-domain features are trained to predict the teacher’s outputs from the previous timestep, forming a smooth trajectory. Further, we design a Hierarchical Illumination Prior (HIP) module that decomposes brightness cues into coarse-to-fine levels, injecting them into both spatial and frequency branches at matching scales to guide realistic exposure recovery. HIP is learned end-to-end and adapts to scene content, avoiding overexposure in bright areas. Finally, we employ a wavelet-based frequency decomposition instead of block-DCT to eliminate checkerboard artifacts and support seamless multi-scale fusion. Evaluated on LOL, LOLv2, and SID datasets, DynaFusion-Diffuse is expected to outperform SOTA in both objective metrics and perceptual quality, particularly in preserving fine textures, reducing color distortion, and maintaining natural illumination gradients.",
